e6c34a90-0d37-44fe-a638-72917cedf07c.059e941b-3037-46dd-a2e4-80e43d129d7a.prompt=provider_domain e6c34a90-0d37-44fe-a638-72917cedf07c.17d0c2fc-83a9-44d1-a91d-2872fdce97a0.description=
Takes a reference to XML (in the form of a String) and the specified XPath Query is run against the XML and returns the results in a form of a delimited list. The World Wide Web Consortium (W3C) organization provides the XPath specification (http\://www.w3.org).

Inputs\:
xml - The XML (in the form of a String)

xpathQuery - The XPath Query that is wanted to be run. See Examples in Notes section below.

delimiter- The delimiter used to separate values in the returnResult list. 

Default value\: ,

Result Value\:
returnResult - The result of the operation. If multiple XPaths are defined then this will add the delimiter between each value. There is no final delimiter.

Notes\:
Examples\:
The XPath Query can be specified as a single query in a format similiar to the following\:
/employees/employee[@id\="3"]/*[name()\="name" or name()\="jobDescription" or name()\="salary" or name()\="managerId"]/text()

This would return the following results\:
Goofy,tester,$50,1

Or if more then one XPath query needs to be specified, populate xpathQuery using the XPath concat function.  As an example here is sample of a xpathQuery value using XPath concat function\:
concat(/employees/employee[@id\="2"]/name/text(),',',/employees/employee[@id\="2"]/jobDescription/text(),',',/employees/employee[@id\="2"]/managerId/text(),',',/employees/employee[@id\="2"]/salary/text())

The output using the concat xpathQuery input would return the following results\:
Donald Duck,Lead Coder,1,$50

The examples above use the following xml string value\:


  
    Mickey Mouse
    Chief
    $100
    
  
  
    Donald Duck
    Lead Coder
    $50
    1
  
  
    Goofy
    tester
    $50
    1
  
  
    Pluto
    Coder - grade 1
    $25
    2
e6c34a90-0d37-44fe-a638-72917cedf07c.33a3738b-107d-4474-9600-4d5cc6aa7470.description=
Useful Op to keep a running results.
Takes a string input (resultText) and appends this to a global context key of "runningResults". As a result, the context key whose name is in the keyName input will be appended with the string from the input resultText.

Input Parameters\:
keyName - name of context key to append to
resultText - string input to append
delimiter - (leave blank for none) the delimiter to put between what is already in keyName before appending resultText

Responses\:
success - assigned the context variable

Returns\:
The the value of the context variable it appended to.

Context\:
runningResults

Scriptlet Example\:
currentResults \= scriptletContext.get("runningResults");

if (currentResults \=\= null) {
   currentResults \= resultText;
} else {
   currentResults +\= resultText;
}


scriptletContext.putGlobal("runningResults", currentResults);
e6c34a90-0d37-44fe-a638-72917cedf07c.3aca8274-fc9a-4f4f-92d5-3c9584a500c2.description=
This workflow returns the details of the given artifact id.

Inputs-
artifactId –   Artifact  Id
userIdentifier  - User Identifier id
authType - The authentication type that this operation uses when trying to execute the request on the target server.
Valid values\: basic, form, digest, ntlm, kerberos, anonymous (no authentication).
Default value\: anonymous - authentication not used when executing the request.
kerberosConfFile - The path to the Kerberos configuration file. If this input is empty the kdc (Key Distribution Center) and realm will get their values from the full domain name which is obtained from the url of the web server.
timeout - The number of milliseconds to wait for a connection to be established. This input should be assigned a value greater than or equal to zero. A timeout value of zero is an infinite timeout.
Default value\: 0.
socketTimeout - The number of milliseconds to wait for the data to be retrieved. This input should be assigned a value greater than or equal to zero. A socketTimeout value of zero is an infinite timeout.
Default value\: 0.
useCookies - If true, enables cookie tracking. Cookies will be stored between consecutive calls. This is a boolean input. If a non-boolean value is specified, it will take the default value.
Default value\: true.
followRedirects - If true, the GET command automatically follows redirects. This is a boolean input. If a non-boolean value is specified, it will take the default value.
Default value\: true
proxy - A proxy to use when accessing the web site.
proxyPort - The port on the proxy to connect to.
proxyUsername - The username to use when connecting to the proxy.
proxyPassword - The password to use when connecting to the proxy.
encodeURL - If true, automatically encodes the URL. This is a boolean input. If a non-boolean value is specified, it will take the default value.
Default value\: false.
userAgent - The value that should be used if the HTTP header USER_AGENT has to be overridden.
trustAllRoots - If true, enables weak security over SSL. A SSL certificate is trusted even if no trusted CA issued it.
Default value\: true
keystore - URL of the keystore file or local path to it (e.g. %JAVA_HOME%/jre/lib/security/cacerts). It may be empty if HTTPS client authentication is not to be used.
keystorePassword - Password to unlock the keystore.
trustKeystore - URL of the truststore file or local path to it (e.g. %JAVA_HOME%/jre/lib/security/cacerts). It may be empty if HTTPS server authentication is not to be used.
trustPassword - Password to unlock the truststore.

Outputs-
name –  name of the artifactr 
displayName – display name of the artifact
artifactType – Artifact type
state – state of the artifact
lifeCycleState –  life cycle state of the artifact
lifeCycleSubState – life cycle sub state of the artifact
document  – returned XML document from API

e6c34a90-0d37-44fe-a638-72917cedf07c.c0e84e5b-743a-4f99-b334-9b23cd4a5d9f.prompt=provider_username e6c34a90-0d37-44fe-a638-72917cedf07c.d099e81c-d089-417c-8cf4-153d133f95d3.description=
This operation loops as many times as specified in the "count" input, counting from "1" to a greater number, incrementing it by "1" at each iteration.

Inputs\:
    count - The number of loops to complete.
Valid values\: from 1 to 9223372036854775807
    reset - Specifies whether the counter restarts counting from "1".
Valid values\: true, false
Default value\: false
    to - The number to count to. It will take the value of the "count" input field. 
    from - The number to start counting at. For this operation, it is customized to "1".
    incrementBy - The number to increment by while counting. For this operation, it is customized to "1".

Results\:
    resultString – This is the primary output. It contains the value of the number that was just counted.

Responses\:
    has more – The counting process is not complete. One or more iterations are pending.
    no more – The counting process is complete.
    failure - The operation completed unsuccessfully.

Note\:
1. It is recommended that you do not change the values of the "to", "from" or "incrementBy" input fields.
2. The "from", "to" and "incrementBy" inputs are customized for this operation. Even though you can also customize them, if you need to specify the loop range borders and the increment value, use the "Counter" operation.

Examples\:
1. For a loop with 20 iterations, the following values should be provided for the input fields\:
    count\: 20
    reset\: false (this field can also be left blank, as "false" is the default value)
2. For an infinite loop, the value of "count" should be at least "1" and the value of "reset" should be "true".

e6c34a90-0d37-44fe-a638-72917cedf07c.f76dffc9-1595-4769-8daf-ae8617605072.description=Converts a JSON array or a JSON object to a XML document. Inputs\: json - The JSON array or object (in the form of a String). prettyPrint - The flag for formatting the resulted XML. If it is true the result will contain tabs and newline chars. Default value\: true Valid values\: true, false showXmlDeclaration - The flag for showing the xml declaration (). If this is true then rootTagName can't be empty. Default value\: false Valid values\: true, false rootTagName - The XML tag name. If this input is empty you will get a list of XML elements. defaultJsonArrayItemName - Default XML tag name for items in a JSON array if there isn't a pair (array name, array item name) defined in jsonArraysNames and jsonArraysItemNames. Default value\: item jsonArraysNames - The list of array names separated by delimiter. Examples\: f\:properties jsonArraysItemNames - The coresponding list of array item names separated by delimiter. Examples\: f\:property namespacesPrefixes - The list of tag prefixes separated by delimiter. Examples\: f,ui namespacesUris - The coresponding list of namespaces uris separated by delimiter. Examples\: http\://java.sun.com/jsf/core,urn\:x-hp\:2012\:software\:eve\:uibinding delimiter - The list separator. Default value\: , Results\: returnResult - This is the primary output. The resulted XML document or XML elements. returnCode - 0 for success; -1 for failure. Responses\: success - The operation completed as stated in the description. failure - The operation completed unsuccessfully. Examples\: 1. json\={ "name"\:"John", "age"\:100, "retired"\:true, "otherInfo"\:null } and the other values with their default values you wil get John 100 true Null values are not converted to XML elements. 2. json\=[{"key"\:"year", "value"\:2013}, {"key"\:"month", "value"\:"11"}] and the other values with their default values you wil get year 2013 month 11 3. A complex example that uses all the inputs\: prettyPrint\=true showXmlDeclaration\=true rootTagName\=myroot defaultJsonArrayItemName\=myitem, jsonArraysNames\=f\:properties jsonArraysItemNames\=f\:property namespacesPrefixes\=f,ui namespacesUris\=http\://java.sun.com/jsf/core,urn\:x-hp\:2012\:software\:eve\:uibinding delimiter\=, json\= { "@id"\:"Page1", "ui\:position"\: { "x"\:1, "y"\:2 }, "f\:properties"\: [ { "key1"\:"value1" }, { "key2"\:"value2" } ], "details"\: [ { "type"\:"size", "height"\:10, "width"\:10 }, { "type"\:"color", "name"\:"blue" } ] } The the result will be\: 1 2 value1 value2
size 10 10 color blue
